"Biastoch A., Treude T., Rpke L.H., Riebesell U., Roth C., Burwicz E.B., Park W., Latif M., Böning C.W., Madec G., Wallmann K.","Rising Arctic Ocean temperatures cause gas hydrate destabilization and ocean acidification",2011,"Geophysical Research Letters","38","8", L08602,"","",,,10.1029/2011GL047222,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79955030837&partnerID=40&md5=9c73e8109efcb755a15ccbc188483837","Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Laboratoire d'Océ Anographie et du Climat, Expé Rimentation et Approches Numérique, 4, Place Jussieu, F-7525 Paris Cedex 05, France","Biastoch, A., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Treude, T., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Rpke, L.H., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Riebesell, U., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Roth, C., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Burwicz, E.B., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Park, W., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Latif, M., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Böning, C.W., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; Madec, G., Laboratoire d'Océ Anographie et du Climat, Expé Rimentation et Approches Numérique, 4, Place Jussieu, F-7525 Paris Cedex 05, France; Wallmann, K., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Universität Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR), Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany","Vast amounts of methane hydrates are potentially stored in sediments along the continental margins, owing their stability to low temperature - high pressure conditions. Global warming could destabilize these hydrates and cause a release of methane (CH<inf>4</inf>) into the water column and possibly the atmosphere. Since the Arctic has and will be warmed considerably, Arctic bottom water temperatures and their future evolution projected by a climate model were analyzed. The resulting warming is spatially inhomogeneous, with the strongest impact on shallow regions affected by Atlantic inflow. Within the next 100 years, the warming affects 25% of shallow and mid-depth regions containing methane hydrates. Release of methane from melting hydrates in these areas could enhance ocean acidification and oxygen depletion in the water column. The impact of methane release on global warming, however, would not be significant within the considered time span. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Acidification; Anoxic sediments; Climate models; Global warming; Hydration; Methane; Oxygen; Arctic ocean; Bottom water; Continental margin; High-pressure condition; Low temperatures; Methane hydrates; Oxygen depletion; Spatially inhomogeneous; Time span; Water columns; Gas hydrates; acidification; air-sea interaction; carbon emission; continental margin; future prospect; gas hydrate; global warming; high pressure; low pressure; methane; oxygen; water column; water temperature; Arctic Ocean",,,,,,"Bartdorff, O., Wallmann, K., Latif, M., Semenov, V., Phanerozoic evolution of atmospheric methane (2008) Global Biogeochemical Cycles, 22 (1), pp. GB1008. , DOI 10.1029/2007GB002985; Biastoch, A., Böning, C.W., Getzlaff, J., Molines, J.-M., Madec, G., Causes of interannual-decadal variability in the meridional overturning circulation of t